HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1098
By Jones J
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Reverend Dr. Bernard
Lafayette, Jr.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Reverend Dr. Bernard Lafayette, Jr.; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Bernard Lafayette's life of courage, faith, and unwavering dedication to
justice helped shape the course of the American Civil Rights Movement, and his commitment to
nonviolent social change inspired generations to pursue equality through peaceful action; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Lafayette emerged as one of the central figures of the Civil Rights
Movement of the 1960s, playing a key role in many of the defining events of the struggle for
racial equality and voting rights in the United States; and
WHEREAS, as a young seminary student in Nashville in 1960, Dr. Bernard Lafayette
joined fellow activists John Lewis, Diane Nash, James Bevel, and others in organizing the
historic Nashville sit-in movement, a disciplined campaign of nonviolent protest that challenged
segregation at lunch counters and public accommodations and ultimately led to the
desegregation of Nashville's downtown commercial district; and
WHEREAS, during this formative period, Dr. Lafayette was deeply influenced by the
philosophy and practice of nonviolent resistance, participating in workshops and trainings that
prepared activists to confront violence and injustice with courage, discipline, and moral
conviction; and
WHEREAS, in April 1960, Dr. Bernard Lafayette joined student leaders from across the
South in founding the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, an organization that quickly
became one of the most influential forces of the Civil Rights Movement and played a vital role in
organizing grassroots campaigns for justice throughout the region; and
