- 1 -

WHEREAS, Dr. Lafayette soon placed himself on the front lines of the movement's most
dangerous struggles, joining the Freedom Rides of 1961, in which activists challenged the
continued segregation of interstate transportation despite federal court rulings declaring such
segregation unlawful; and
WHEREAS, during the Freedom Rides, Dr. Bernard Lafayette and his fellow riders faced
brutal violence from white mobs determined to preserve segregation, yet they remained
steadfast in their commitment to nonviolence, refusing to retaliate even when attacked and
beaten; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Lafayette was arrested in Jackson, Mississippi, for his participation in
the Freedom Rides and was imprisoned along with hundreds of other civil rights activists at the
notorious Mississippi State Penitentiary at Parchman Farm, where he remained incarcerated for
more than a month for his peaceful protest against racial injustice; and
WHEREAS, undeterred by violence, imprisonment, and threats against his life, Dr.
Bernard Lafayette committed himself fully to the cause of civil rights and soon undertook some
of the most challenging organizing work of the era; and
WHEREAS, in 1962, he became director of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating
Committee's Alabama Voter Registration Project and, together with his wife, the civil rights
advocate Colia Liddell Lafayette, moved to Selma, Alabama, where they organized local citizens
in churches, homes, and community spaces to challenge the systematic denial of voting rights
to African Americans; and
WHEREAS, the Lafayettes' patient and courageous organizing efforts in Selma laid the
groundwork for the historic Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights campaign, which culminated in
the fifty-four-mile march that galvanized national attention and helped lead to the passage of the
Voting Rights Act of 1965, one of the most significant civil rights laws in American history; and
WHEREAS, during these years of struggle, Dr. Lafayette endured repeated arrests,
brutal attacks, and constant threats to his safety, yet he remained firmly committed to the
- 2 - 015424

philosophy of nonviolence, even in moments of extreme danger, demonstrating extraordinary
courage and moral leadership; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Lafayette later became a close associate and trusted lieutenant of the
Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., working alongside Dr. King in advancing the cause of civil
rights and economic justice and helping to organize the Poor People's Campaign, an effort to
unite Americans of all races in the fight against poverty and inequality; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Bernard Lafayette was present in Memphis during the sanitation
workers' strike that brought Dr. King to the city in 1968, standing alongside his fellow civil rights
leaders during one of the most pivotal and tragic moments in the movement's history; and
WHEREAS, following the height of the Civil Rights Movement, Dr. Lafayette devoted his
life to preserving and expanding the philosophy of nonviolent social change, dedicating himself
to education, leadership development, and the empowerment of future generations; and
WHEREAS, as an educator, minister, and international lecturer, he conducted
workshops, seminars, and training programs on nonviolence across the United States and
around the world, helping communities address conflict and injustice through peaceful means
and equipping new generations with the tools of disciplined activism; and
WHEREAS, through decades of teaching and mentorship, Dr. Bernard Lafayette
empowered countless young leaders to carry forward the principles of courage, compassion,
and nonviolent resistance that defined the Civil Rights Movement; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Lafayette's life stands as a testament to the transformative power of
faith, perseverance, and moral conviction, and his contributions to the struggle for civil rights
helped expand democracy and freedom for millions of Americans; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Reverend Dr. Bernard Lafayette, Jr., reflecting
- 3 - 015424

fondly upon his impeccable character, his steadfast commitment to nonviolent social change,
and his enduring contributions to the Civil Rights Movement and the advancement of justice.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Dr. Lafayette.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 4 - 015424

